[1] Canada - Saskatchewan
Date: Thu 28 Apr 2005
From: Sylvia Macbean <s.macbean@sasktel.net>
Source: CBC News online, Saskatchewan, Wed 2 Feb 2005 [edited]
<http://sask.cbc.ca/regional/servlet/View?filename=hantavirus050202>


Saskatchewan: Indian Reserve Concerned About Hantavirus
-------------------------------------------------------
A northern 1st Nation is taking precautions after a deadly case of
hantavirus infection. A woman from Pelican Narrows fell ill last month
[April 2005] and died from the disease, which is spread by deer mice. A
preliminary investigation suggests she contracted hantavirus in a home in
Pelican Narrows. Now, people living there are being urged to take steps to
prevent it from happening again. Health officials are also urging calm,
saying the disease is rare. "This is not a reason to panic," said Mandiangu
Nsungu, the region's medical health officer. "The proportion of mice that
are able to transmit hantavirus is very small."

Meanwhile, Chief Ron Michel of Peter Ballantyne Cree Nation is asking
people in the region to take steps to prevent the spread of hantavirus.
"I've been telling my people...to try and clean up their yards where these
rodents populate," he said. Michel has also ordered inspections for all
public buildings operated by the 1st Nation. One school with a history of
mouse problems has been temporarily shut down at Deschambault Lake.

The Pelican Narrows case is the province's 16th case of hantavirus in 10
years. It's also the 5th fatality from the disease.

--
Sylvia Macbean
<s.macbean@sasktel.net>

[ProMED-mail regrets the delay in posting this information on this
hantavirus pulmonary syndrome case in Saskatchewan, which occurred prior to
the death of the Albertan women in April 2005, posted as "Hantavirus
