[2] USA - Colorado
Date: Fri 29 Apr 2005
From: Michael A. Olesen <Michael.Olesen@allina.com>


Rodent Population Dynamics, Raptors, Climate and Virus Interactions
---------------------------------------------------
The case of hantavirus infection in Colorado led me to post some thoughts I
had about the interaction between hantaviruses, West Nile virus (WNV), and
climate.

It is well known that WNV has had a negative impact on raptor populations.
What seems less understood is whether this impact has much influence on
rodent populations. My premise is that because the raptors in part help
control rodent populations, a rodent bloom could appear when raptor
populations are diminished.

The other piece that seems to play a role in this is climate. WNV activity
seems to be lower in dry years. This seems to have been the case in 2004.
However, wetter climates probably increase both WNV activity as well as the
potential for hantavirus activity. Clearly mosquito activity is much higher
in a moist season. The outbreak of hantavirus infection in the 4 Corners
regions has been linked to a moist season as well, which allow rodent
populations to bloom after the moisture increased the food supply.

The questions that remains to be answered is whether hantavirus activity
will increase beyond what is expected due to the combination of wet climate
and smaller raptor populations. This may also hold true for other diseases
with life cycles including rodents in areas with raptor populations heavily
affected by WNV.

--
Michael Olesen
Infection Control Practitioner
Abbott-Northwestern Hospital
800 East 28th Street
Minneapolis, MN 55407-3799
<michael.olesen@allina.com>

