[4] USA - New Mexico
Date: Sat 30 Apr 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: NCTimes.com, Associated Press report, Fri 29 Apr 2005 [edited]
<http://www.nctimes.com/articles/2005/04/30/special_reports/science_technology/20_41_184_29_05.txt>


2nd Hantavirus Patient Being Treated in Albuquerque
------------------------------------------------------
The University of New Mexico Hospital was treating its 2nd hantavirus
patient of the month on Friday [29 Apr 2005], but health officials said
they aren't yet sure if a rise in cases of the potentially fatal disease is
imminent this year.

The 32-year-old woman from southern Colorado admitted to the hospital on
Wednesday was in satisfactory condition on Friday, hospital spokeswoman
Cindy Foster said.

A 29-year-old man from northeastern Arizona, admitted earlier this month
with hantavirus, remained in critical condition. The man had been treated
with an extracorporeal membrane oxygenation, or ECMO, machine, but is no
longer on it. The hospital has used ECMO to treat patients with hantavirus
pulmonary syndrome. The machine puts oxygen in the blood and helps pump it
through the body, making up for the infection weakening the lungs and heart.

Experts have warned the wet weather of winter and early spring could mean
higher populations of mice this year in the West. "The increase in moisture
and increase in vegetation can lead to an increase in rodent population,"
said Dr. Bernadette Albanese, a medical epidemiologist with the New Mexico
Department of Health. Albanese said about 10 percent of the deer mice in
New Mexico are infected with hantavirus. "Having more mice around can
increase the likelihood a human will come in contact with mice droppings or
urine, but the question that I can't answer is if having more mice around
will increase the percentage of mice that will be infected," Albanese said.

The conditions this year have been likened by experts to 1993, when the
disease was first identified in the 4 Corners area. The outbreak killed 10
people and led to identification of hantavirus pulmonary syndrome. Albanese
said hantavirus remains a relatively rare disease, but added, "the risk is
there and it's high enough to be concerned."

Hantavirus is passed to humans when they inhale particles of dried urine or
feces from infected rodents, especially deer mice. The problem most often
occurs when people enter buildings such as cabins or sheds that have been
closed for a while and have been infested by mice. The illness is marked by
fever, headache and muscle ache, possibly with chills, nausea and vomiting,
and progresses rapidly to severe difficulty in breathing and, in some
cases, death. Symptoms develop one to 6 weeks after exposure.

Health officials advise that anyone entering a building that has been
closed up for several months and may be infested by mice wear a face mask
and gloves and use a bleach solution to wet and clean up any mouse nests or
droppings.

New Mexico has recorded a total of 63 cases of hantavirus. 27 of those
cases have been fatal, according to numbers released by the state in
December 2004, when a man contracted hantavirus while searching for
Christmas decorations in a storage shed.

