[5] USA - Nebraska
Date: Sat 7 May 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Press & Dakotan, Associated Press report, 7 May 2005 [edited]


Nebraskan Dies From Hantavirus Pulmonary Syndrome
-------------------------------------------------
A western Nebraska man in his early 50s died last month [April 2005] after
being infected with hantavirus, a virus which is spread through the urine,
droppings or saliva of infected rodents, state officials said. Humans can
contract the virus by inhaling.

The man who died in late April worked in a rural agricultural setting. He
saw his doctor after becoming ill and was hospitalized the next day in
North Platte, then transferred to the Nebraska Medical Center in Omaha,
said Dr. Tom Safranek, state epidemiologist.

The man is the 4th person in Nebraska to die of the disease. 9 cases have
been confirmed since the virus was first reported in the state in 1998,
according to state records. 2 possible cases have not been resolved.

Hantavirus pulmonary syndrome attacks the lungs, destroying air sacs and
preventing the movement of oxygen into the body, Safranek said. The disease
was virtually unheard of [i.e. unrecognised - Mod.CP] in the United States
until an outbreak occurred in May 1993 in an area where New Mexico,
Arizona, Colorado and Utah meet.

